    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Lou is generally understood to mean a multi-story building (two stories or more) or a loft-building (Kroll 2015, 281) elevated on a terrace or city wall. Historically, lou as a type of traditional architecture usually designates a building elevated either by means of multiple stories or man-made or natural platforms. The Eastern Han dynasty (25-220 CE) classic Shuowen jiezi defines lou as a structure with a layered wu 屋 (a roof, or a roofed structure).</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
